results.reasoning: External bilobed abdominal contour with central depression and US showing two hemicavities separated by a thin central septum with placenta in one horn and fetal parts in both suggests a bicornuate uterus with intercornual communication rather than a septate or arcuate uterus or synechiae.

Chronic left lumbar pain with long-standing anemia and mild leukocytosis suggests chronic destructive renal infection. Imaging indicates an enlarged non-functioning kidney with multiple low-attenuation areas consistent with diffuse xanthogranulomatous pyelonephritis. Acute pyonephrosis is usually more fulminant, hydronephrosis does not cause systemic inflammation, TB is less likely in this pediatric case, and a tumor is less consistent with the chronic inflammatory picture.

Well-circumscribed enhancing pineal-region mass causing obstructive hydrocephalus; biopsy taken at ETV and excellent response to radiotherapy — classic for a radiosensitive intracranial germ cell tumour (germinoma).

Preoperative barium enema demonstrates extraluminal contrast in the pelvis and postoperative CT shows densely hyperattenuating particulate material within a pelvic collection (visible on 3D VR) consistent with retained extraluminal enteric contrast/barium rather than urinoma, simple seroma, or isolated abscess.

Lobulated, solid mass on the volar wrist intimately associated with the tendon sheath showing heterogeneous signal with low-signal foci (likely hemosiderin) and marked enhancement — features most consistent with giant-cell tumor of tendon sheath (localized tenosynovial giant cell tumor).

Cystic multilocular mesenteric lesion in left flank with enhancing wall and surrounding inflammatory changes on CT and complex cystic appearance on US; no history of pancreatitis and no bowel-wall signature to suggest duplication—most consistent with lymphangioma with inflammation.

Transabdominal ultrasound shows a thin central intrauterine septum dividing the cavity into two hemicavities with placenta on left side and fetus in right. Thin midline septum (not external fundal cleft or two separate uteri) is typical of a septate uterus with septal placental implantation.

Chronic left flank symptoms with prolonged anemia and leukocytosis plus imaging features consistent with an enlarged kidney showing multiple hypodense, rim‑enhancing calyceal cavities (bear‑paw sign), cortical thinning, staghorn calculus and perinephric inflammatory changes — classic for diffuse xanthogranulomatous pyelonephritis.

Midline pineal/tectal enhancing solid mass causing obstructive hydrocephalus in an adult male with biopsy-proven diagnosis and excellent response to radical radiotherapy — imaging pattern of a homogeneously enhancing pineal lesion (likely engulfs calcification) and marked radiosensitivity is most consistent with an intracranial germ cell tumour/germinoma.

CT-urography demonstrates extravasation of opacified urine into a pelvic collection with a visible contrast-filled tract on delayed/excretory images and 3D reconstructions, consistent with an iatrogenic ureteral injury with urinoma.

Well-defined volar tendon-sheath mass isointense to muscle on T1 and heterogeneous on T2 without imaging features of hemosiderin/blooming. Pattern and location favour tenosynovial fibroma (fibroma of tendon sheath) over ganglion or GCTTS.

Thick-walled, unilocular cystic mass in left abdomen with layered ‘gut-signature’ on ultrasound, wall hyperemia and surrounding inflammatory changes on CT—findings most consistent with an infected enteric duplication cyst (enteric duplication).
